You’re very close. Since the files are already on GitHub, the next things are about making collaboration safe and organized.

What to do next:
1. Make sure both of you have the repo cloned on your own computers.
2. Invite your partner to the GitHub repository as a collaborator.
3. Decide a simple workflow:
   - you work mainly on backend/Rust
   - she works mainly on frontend
   - each feature goes on its own branch
4. Pull the latest version from GitHub before starting work each day.
5. Push your changes regularly.

A simple workflow that should work well:
- `main` branch stays stable
- you create branches like:
  - `backend/dehaze-tuning`
  - `backend/raw-loader`
- she creates branches like:
  - `frontend/tester-ui`
  - `frontend/layout-pass`
- when one of you finishes something, merge it into `main`

The commands you’ll probably use most are:

```powershell
git pull
git checkout -b backend/some-feature
git add .
git commit -m "Implement some feature"
git push -u origin backend/some-feature
```

And to get changes from the other person:

```powershell
git checkout main
git pull
```

Very important practical advice:
- don’t both edit the same files at the same time unless necessary
- separate responsibilities early
- define how frontend talks to backend before she starts building too much UI

For your project, a good split is:
- you: Rust engine, image processing, preview/export logic
- her: interface, controls, visual layout, frontend interaction

What I would recommend right now:
- make sure your local folder is connected cleanly to the GitHub repo
- create a small README section for collaboration rules
- define the future boundary between frontend and backend

If you want, I can help you with the exact next step depending on your situation:
- if your local folder is not connected to the GitHub repo yet, I can help set that up
- if it is connected already, I can help you create a clean branch workflow
- or I can help structure the project now so you and your partner can work in parallel without conflicts
